{{Refimprove|date=February 2017}} {{Infobox magazine| title = Airliners | image_file = Airliners novdec04.jpg | image_size = 200px || editor = | frequency = Bimonthly | category = [[Airlines]] / [[Airliners]] | company = Airliners Publications, LLC | founded = 1988| country = United States| based = Castro Valley, California | language = English | website = [http://www.airliners.tv/ www.airliners.tv] | issn = 0896-6575 }}
'''''Airliners''''' was an American magazine dedicated to the airline industry. Six issues were circulated each year. The title was first published by [[World Transport Press]] in 1988. Since the 100th issue (July/August 2006) it was produced by Airliners Publications, LLC. For a time, the editorial headquarters of the magazine was in [[Castro Valley, California]], although it later was based in Miami.<ref>{{cite book|author=Judy Colbert|title=Career Opportunities in the Travel Industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFtsRqPC1FIC&pg=PA226|accessdate=16 February 2016|date=1 January 2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1088-2|page=226}}</ref>
The magazine included articles about the world of commercial aircraft and air carriers, including new [[low cost airlines]], changes at legacy companies, jetliners such as the [[Airbus A380]] and [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787]], trips around the world, historical airlines, adventurous flights, airliner crashes and pictures of airliner liveries.
Featured authors include John Adlard, Sebastian Schmitz, Dave Nichols, Ben Wang, Bill Hough, [[Joel Chusid]], Royal King, Robbie Shaw, and Cody Diamond. Photographers contributed images of airlines, aircraft, personnel, facilities and operations.
The magazine's first editor was John Wegg, who left Airliners to found [[Airways Magazine]] in 1994. Subsequent editors were Bryant Pettit, Nick Veronico, Jon Proctor, David Kaufman and Jay Selman. Starting with the November/December 2007 issue, the editor was Dwayne Darnell. On December 11, 2009, Darnell announced that he was leaving, and that designer/Creative Director Robert Christensen would lead the magazine.
In 2010, Robert Christensen announced plans for a series of online initiatives, releasing e-book formats of the print magazine and establishing a social media presence. The magazine was re-titled "Airliners & Airports. Popular components of past issues such as the Air Photo News section were being returned to the magazine's pages, but around the end of 2012 the magazine abruptly ceased publishing and the website is no longer active.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nycaviation.com/forum/threads/43049-Anybody-Know-Whether-Airliners-magazine-is-still-being-Published |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-06-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817204336/http://nycaviation.com/forum/threads/43049-Anybody-Know-Whether-Airliners-magazine-is-still-being-Published |archive-date=2016-08-17 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
