{{Infobox book |image = All the Devils Are Here.jpg |image_size = 200 |border = yes |author = [[Bethany McLean]] and [[Joseph Nocera]] |name = All the Devils Are Here |country = United States |language = English |subject = [[Economic History]], Finance |publisher = Portfolio/[[Penguin Press]] |release_date = November 16, 2010 |media_type = Hardcover |isbn = 1-59184-363-4 |dewey = |congress = |oclc = 535490487 |pages = 400 pp. }}
'''''All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis''''' is a nonfiction book by authors [[Bethany McLean]] and [[Joseph Nocera]] about the [[Financial crisis of 2007–2010|2008 financial crisis.]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = All the Devils are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VWyI9EAqpYsC|publisher = Portfolio/Penguin|date = 2010-01-01|isbn = 9781591843634|language = en|first = Bethany|last = McLean|first2 = Joseph|last2 = Nocera}}</ref> It details how the financial crisis bubbled up from a volatile, and bipartisan, mixture of government meddling and ''[[laissez-faire]]''. It concludes it was not an accident, that banks understood the big picture before the crisis happened but continued with bad practices.
== The title == The title of the book comes from [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Tempest]]'', in which he wrote "Hell is empty, and all the devils are here".
