'''Wagner's Point''' is an industrial area in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]].<ref>Earl Arnett, Robert J. Brugger, [[Edward C. Papenfuse]] (1999). [https://books.google.com/books?id=lncOLHYhcrsC&pg=PA346&dq=%22wagner's+point%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&cd=21 ''Maryland: A New Guide to the Old Line State'', p. 346.]  The Johns Hopkins University Press. {{ISBN|0-8018-5979-4}}. Retrieved 2010-05-17.</ref>

The name of the area comes from the Martin Wagner Company, which operated a beef packing plant there before the property was acquired by the Baltimore City government.<ref>The Catholic Editing Company (1914). [https://books.google.com/books?id=KL4YAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA110&dq=%22wagner's+point%22&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&cd=3 ''The Catholic church in the United of America'', p. 110.] The Plimpton Press. Retrieved 2008-04-11.</ref> The Martin Wagner plant was destroyed by a fire in 1913.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NRcpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA36&dq=%22wagner's+point%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&cd=56 |title=Ice and Refrigeration, p. 36 |publisher=Nickerson & Collins Co.|date=December 1913 |accessdate=2011-01-03}}</ref> The City of Baltimore operates its Patapsco Waste Water Treatment Plant on the former Martin Wagner site.

Until the late 1990s Wagner's Point included a residential community which was relocated by the City due to environmental concerns.<ref>Robert C. Keith (2005). [https://books.google.com/books?id=zgoUCozUOdgC&pg=PA75&dq=%22wagner's+point%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&cd=11 ''Baltimore harbor: a pictorial history'', p. 75.]  The Johns Hopkins University Press. Retrieved 2010-05-17</ref> Negotiations with the final 270 residents of Wagner's Point over the city's buyout was bitterly disputed. Representatives of the residents walked out of the third negotiation session on September 17, 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1998-09-18/news/1998261049_1_wagner-appraisals-locust-point |title=Wagner's Point negotiations end abruptly|author=Joe Matthews |work=The Baltimore Sun |date=September 18, 1998 |accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> Houses of the former residents were demolished after the city's [[buyout]] of the properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypaper.com/news/story.asp?id=4927 |title=Point of No Return: It's All Over but the Shouting for Wagner's Point |work=Baltimore City Paper|date=February 16, 2000 |accessdate=2010-05-17|author=Michael Anft}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-07-20/news/9907200048_1_rowhouse-exit-nostalgia |title=Barely looking back at old Wagner's Point |work=The Baltimore Sun |date=July 20, 1999|author=Joe Matthews|accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref><ref>Steve Lerner (2005).[https://books.google.com/books?id=BNMpKkIa4MsC&pg=PA80&dq=%22wagner's+point%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&cd=27 ''Diamond: a struggle for environmental justice in Louisiana's chemical corridor'', p. 80.] MIT Press. {{ISBN|0-262-12273-1}}.</ref>



